## Cargo workspace rules

### Mock workspace

- All hilavitkutin crates use `version.workspace = true`,
  `edition.workspace = true`, `license.workspace = true`.
- Sibling dependencies use `.workspace = true` syntax.
- External dependencies declared in `[workspace.dependencies]`.
- Edition 2024 for all crates.

### Crate structure

Nine crates total: eight plain `rlib` crates plus one proc-macro
crate. Flat structure.

- `hilavitkutin-api` is the consumer-facing contract crate. Traits
  and data shapes only; no concrete engine logic.
- `hilavitkutin` is the engine. Depends on `hilavitkutin-api` and
  on arvo crates.
- `hilavitkutin-build` is build-dep only. Declared under
  `[build-dependencies]` in the consumer, never under
  `[dependencies]`. No runtime linkage.
- `hilavitkutin-ctx`, `hilavitkutin-persistence`, `hilavitkutin-str`
  are standalone ecosystem crates. Each is independently usable.
  They do not depend on the engine, on `hilavitkutin-api`, or on
  each other.
- `hilavitkutin-linking` is the cross-platform dynamic library
  loader primitive in the plugin-host layer. `no_std`, no
  allocator. Provides abstractions that downstream consumer hosts
  (viola, loimu, etc.) use to load their own cdylib extensions.
  Depends only on notko / arvo / arvo-bits and on libc /
  windows-sys for raw FFI. Must never depend on
  `hilavitkutin-api`, `hilavitkutin`, or any other hilavitkutin
  crate. Renamed from prior `hilavitkutin-extensions` in round
  202604240615.
- `hilavitkutin-extensions` is the contract-bound host orchestration
  layered over `hilavitkutin-linking`. Owns descriptor shape,
  pull-based discovery, lifecycle, capability dispatch, failure
  policy. `no_std`, no allocator, no dyn. Depends on
  `hilavitkutin-linking` plus notko and arvo.
- `hilavitkutin-extensions-macros` is the proc-macro companion to
  `hilavitkutin-extensions`. It ships `#[export_extension]` which
  emits the repr-C descriptor, exported-symbol fn, capability
  table, and per-capability trampolines on behalf of an extension
  author. The only proc-macro crate in the stack. Its emitted
  output is `no_std`-compatible.

### Plugin host crates (layer, not loophole)

The three plugin-host crates (`hilavitkutin-linking`,
`hilavitkutin-extensions`, `hilavitkutin-extensions-macros`) layer
into a reusable downstream-consumer loader foundation:

```
  hilavitkutin-extensions-macros  (proc-macro, emits against host)
          |
          +-- emitted output references ---v
  hilavitkutin-extensions          (contract host, rlib)
          |
          v (consumes)
  hilavitkutin-linking             (dlopen primitive, rlib)
          |
          v (platform FFI)
  OS dynamic loader
```

`hilavitkutin-linking` and `hilavitkutin-extensions` are plain
`rlib`s. They provide abstractions for loading and orchestrating
cdylib extensions; they are not cdylib targets themselves. No
hilavitkutin crate is a cdylib target. The dynamic `cdylib`
ecosystems exist only downstream of this layer, in consumer hosts
(viola, future loimu, future clause extension surfaces).

This layering is deliberate. The engine stays at strict static
composition; downstream consumers get a reusable plugin-host
foundation without every consumer rewriting raw dlopen or
reinventing descriptor formats.

### Dependency direction

- `hilavitkutin-api`: no hilavitkutin crate deps. May depend on
  arvo if it needs numeric types. Must never depend on
  `hilavitkutin` (circular).
- `hilavitkutin` depends on `hilavitkutin-api` plus arvo.
- `hilavitkutin-build`: zero hilavitkutin crate deps; may depend on
  LLVM / cargo / rustc toolchain crates. Strictly build-time.
- `hilavitkutin-ctx`, `-persistence`, `-str`: independent. Each
  may depend on arvo; none depend on the engine or on
  each other.
- `hilavitkutin-linking`: depends only on notko / arvo / arvo-bits
  and on libc (unix) / windows-sys (windows) for raw FFI.
  Must never depend on `hilavitkutin-api`, `hilavitkutin`, or any
  other hilavitkutin crate.
- `hilavitkutin-extensions`: depends on `hilavitkutin-linking`
  plus notko and arvo. Must never depend on `hilavitkutin-api`,
  `hilavitkutin`, `hilavitkutin-build`, or the ecosystem crates.
- `hilavitkutin-extensions-macros`: depends on proc-macro2 + syn +
  quote at macro-execution time. Its emitted output references
  `::hilavitkutin_extensions::*` paths, so downstream consumers
  must add `hilavitkutin-extensions` as a regular dependency
  alongside the macro crate. Must never be depended on at runtime
  by engine, api, build-time, or ecosystem crates.

### `no_std` + `no_alloc` enforcement

Every rlib crate's `lib.rs` starts with:

```rust
#![no_std]
#![deny(unsafe_op_in_unsafe_fn)]
// no `extern crate alloc;`
```

`Cargo.toml` must not pull `std`-feature variants of any dependency.
If an arvo crate exposes a `std` feature, it stays off.

`hilavitkutin-extensions-macros` is the sole exception to the
`no_std` rule at the crate level: proc-macro crates run in the
compiler host context and necessarily use `std`. The code the
macro emits must still be `no_std`-compatible.

### ExpandedLto pragma

`hilavitkutin-build` provides the `ExpandedLto` pragma (domain 03
in the consolidation topic). The consumer's release profile must
opt into it. This requirement is documented in
`hilavitkutin-build`'s DESIGN doc; lint enforcement comes later
when the pragma's concrete shape lands.

### Foundations (arvo)

Arvo crates are git dependencies on the workspace dev branch for
now. When both projects stabilise, they become versioned crates.io
releases.

```toml
[workspace.dependencies]
arvo          = { git = "https://github.com/orgrinrt/arvo.git", branch = "dev" }
arvo-bits     = { git = "https://github.com/orgrinrt/arvo.git", branch = "dev" }
arvo-bitmask  = { git = "https://github.com/orgrinrt/arvo.git", branch = "dev" }
arvo-graph    = { git = "https://github.com/orgrinrt/arvo.git", branch = "dev" }
arvo-sparse   = { git = "https://github.com/orgrinrt/arvo.git", branch = "dev" }
arvo-spectral = { git = "https://github.com/orgrinrt/arvo.git", branch = "dev" }
arvo-comb     = { git = "https://github.com/orgrinrt/arvo.git", branch = "dev" }
```

When iterating on changes crossing the arvo / hilavitkutin boundary, add a local `[patch]` temporarily; remove before pushing.

### Arbitrary-time linking (consumer invariant)

The plugin-host layer assumes any extension can be loaded, invoked, and dropped at arbitrary points in the host's execution, independent of other extensions. Consumer code that uses the plugin-host layer MUST tolerate that pattern. Assumptions like "all extensions are loaded before any are invoked", "init ordering gates invocation", or "the ecosystem of extensions must be known before proceeding" are forbidden at the framework level.

The framework intentionally does not build runtime extension discovery. If a downstream consumer (for example loimu) wants runtime discovery semantics, it builds that abstraction in its own consumer layer on top of `hilavitkutin-linking` and `hilavitkutin-extensions`. The base layer supports this by enforcing only arbitrary-time-compatible contracts:

- No global static registry reads in any public API.
- Symbol handles carry loader lifetimes so dropping an extension invalidates symbols at compile time.
- Lifecycle functions are per-extension; no ecosystem-wide init gate.
- Extension descriptors never depend on siblings being loaded.

The invariant propagates forward into `hilavitkutin-extensions` and into any downstream consumer contract crate (viola-plugin-abi etc.). Every layer preserves it or explicitly documents where and why it is broken.

### Forbidden crate types

- No `[lib] proc-macro = true` on any hilavitkutin crate EXCEPT `hilavitkutin-extensions-macros`. Exactly one proc-macro crate in the stack; adding a second requires a design round.
- No `crate-type = ["cdylib"]` on any hilavitkutin crate. The engine composes statically; the plugin-host layer (`hilavitkutin-linking`, `hilavitkutin-extensions`) LOADS cdylibs but is not itself a cdylib target.
- No linker-magic discovery in any hilavitkutin crate. `inventory`, `ctor`, `#[distributed_slice]`, `.init_array`-based registration are banned on both the producer and consumer sides of the loader boundary. `hilavitkutin-linking` and `hilavitkutin-extensions` enforce pull-based explicit-symbol resolution only.
- No runtime WU discovery in the engine. The engine's WorkUnit composition is strictly static. This constraint does not extend to consumer hosts' extension ecosystems, which route through the plugin-host layer.
